<!-- ============================================================ S3: ARCHITECTURE -->
<section id="s3" class="chapter">
  <h2 class="section-title">3. Architecture Overview &amp; The 7 Primitives</h2>

  <h3>3.1 Conceptual Architecture</h3>
  <p>Nex implements a <strong>graph-based virtual machine</strong> where programs are JSON documents — directed graphs of typed nodes connected by typed edges. The interpreter traverses the graph depth-first from an entry node, dispatching each node kind to a handler, and accumulating results in an in-memory map. This is conceptually similar to a dataflow engine or a computational graph (as seen in TensorFlow's static graph mode), but explicitly designed for agent orchestration rather than tensor math.</p>

  <p>The runtime sits behind an HTTP gateway (optionally authenticated in v1.1) and exposes a single <span class="mono">POST /execute</span> endpoint. A WebSocket server is provided for real-time streaming. A self-contained HTML dashboard communicates with the gateway.</p>

  <h3>3.2 The Seven Primitives — Declared vs. Implemented</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Primitive</th><th>Node Kind(s) in Runtime</th><th>Orisha</th><th>Hermetic Law</th><th>Implementation Status</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>node</strong></td><td>goal, agent, memory, tool, guard, rewrite, reflect, merge, parallel</td><td>Ọbàtálá</td><td>Mentalism</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-good">Implemented</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>link</strong></td><td>sync, async, parallel, depend</td><td>Èṣù</td><td>Correspondence</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-high">Partial — async unimplemented</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>guard</strong></td><td>guard (kind)</td><td>Ògún</td><td>Polarity</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-medium">Shallow — condition eval trivial</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>spawn</strong></td><td>agent (kind) — no dedicated spawn kind</td><td>Ọ̀ṣun</td><td>Gender</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-high">Missing — agent node returns stub</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>rewrite</strong></td><td>rewrite (kind)</td><td>Ọya</td><td>Vibration</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-medium">Stub — returns "applied: true" always</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>merge</strong></td><td>merge (kind)</td><td>Yemọja</td><td>Rhythm</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-good">Implemented — 5 strategies</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>eval</strong></td><td>evalNode() (method) + reflect (kind)</td><td>Ṣàngó</td><td>Cause &amp; Effect</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-good">Implemented</span></td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>3.3 Execution Model Analysis</h3>
  <p>The <span class="mono">NexInterpreter.evalNode()</span> method is the heart of the runtime. It executes recursively and memoizes results in <span class="mono">this.results: Map&lt;string, any&gt;</span>. The memoization correctly prevents double-execution of already-visited nodes — this is the key mechanism intended to handle DAGs (directed acyclic graphs). However:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>No cycle detection:</strong> the <span class="mono">executed</span> set prevents re-execution of a node, but a cycle in the graph (A → B → A) will not loop infinitely because of the early-return on line 87. This is actually safe for pure execution cycles, but the memoization returns whatever was set — which for a cycle would be <span class="mono">undefined</span> (since the map entry hasn't been set yet at first visit). This can cause <span class="mono">undefined</span> result propagation silently without error.</li>
    <li><strong>Parallel branch execution flaw:</strong> The <span class="mono">executeParallel()</span> method fires <span class="mono">Promise.all</span> on outgoing parallel-typed links, but then <span class="mono">evalNode()</span> <em>also</em> independently follows all sync/depend links after the node returns. If a parallel node's targets are also connected via sync links, they get executed twice.</li>
    <li><strong>async link type ignored:</strong> The outgoing link traversal at the end of <span class="mono">evalNode()</span> only follows <span class="mono">sync</span> and <span class="mono">depend</span> typed links. <span class="mono">async</span> typed links are simply never traversed — they are silently dropped.</li>
    <li><strong>depend link semantics:</strong> The <span class="mono">depend</span> link type is documented as "predecessor result is injected into successor's input" but the implementation simply calls <span class="mono">await this.evalNode(nextNode)</span> — there is no actual data injection; the successor must independently look up results from the shared map.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout callout-critical">
    <strong>Critical: Silent data corruption from async links</strong>
    Any graph that uses <span class="mono">"type": "async"</span> links will silently lose those execution paths. Nodes connected only via async links will never execute. This contradicts the documented "fire and forget" behavior and the AGENTS.md specification. Graphs designed around async semantics are effectively broken.
  </div>

  <h3>3.4 Philosophical Grounding — Assessment</h3>
  <p>The mapping of each primitive to a Hermetic Law and an Orisha archetype is consistent and thoughtfully applied throughout the documentation and example graphs. The <span class="mono">bootstrap-2026-debate.json</span> correctly annotates each node with <span class="mono">orisha</span> and <span class="mono">hermetic</span> fields. The guard "Ògún enforces constraints" and merge "Yemọja governs rhythm and convergence" are coherent architectural metaphors, not gratuitous decoration. This is a genuine strength of the project's design language.</p>

  <p>That said, the philosophical framework is not yet formally operative — i.e., there is no enforcement that a <span class="mono">guard</span> node's <span class="mono">orisha</span> field must be "Ògún", or that <span class="mono">hermetic</span> values are from the canonical set. These are metadata-only, not schema-validated constraints.</p>
</section>

<!-- ============================================================ S4: MODULE DEEP DIVE -->
<section id="s4" class="chapter">
  <h2 class="section-title">4. Module-by-Module Deep Dive</h2>

  <h3>4.1 nex-runtime.ts (298 LOC) — Core Interpreter</h3>

  <div class="callout callout-good">
    <strong>Strengths</strong>
    Clean class structure. Clear switch-case dispatch. Proper TypeScript interfaces for NexNode, NexLink, NexGraph. Validation at construction time (fail-fast). All 9 node kinds dispatched. Merge strategies cover 5 patterns. Strong type strictness.
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-critical">
    <strong>Critical Issues in nex-runtime.ts</strong>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>evaluateCondition() is a stub (lines 149-153):</strong> Every string condition evaluates to <span class="mono">true</span> if non-empty. Boolean <span class="mono">false</span> is respected. But any guard with a string condition (e.g., <span class="mono">"role === 'admin'"</span>) always passes. Guards are the primary safety mechanism — this makes them effectively decorative for string-based conditions.</li>
      <li><strong>executeRewrite() is a stub (lines 155-165):</strong> Returns <span class="mono">{ applied: true }</span> without performing any graph mutation. The self-modification capability central to Nex's identity does not exist in the runtime.</li>
      <li><strong>executeAgent() is a stub (lines 218-229):</strong> Returns <span class="mono">{ spawned: true }</span> without creating any actual agent subprocess, thread, or coroutine. Multi-agent execution is entirely simulated.</li>
      <li><strong>spawn node kind absent from switch-case:</strong> The 7 primitives include "spawn" but <span class="mono">NexNode.kind</span> type has no "spawn" variant, and the switch statement has no spawn case. The agent kind is the closest proxy.</li>
      <li><strong>results Map uses <span class="mono">Map&lt;string, any&gt;</span>:</strong> Should be <span class="mono">Map&lt;string, Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;&gt;</span> or a discriminated union for type safety.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>4.2 auth-manager.ts (364 LOC) — Authentication</h3>
  <p>The AuthManager implements a hand-rolled JWT system using Node.js's built-in <span class="mono">crypto</span> module. The structure is sound: RBAC permissions matrix, token blacklisting, session store, graph signing, OAuth2 stub, MFA stub. For a reference implementation it is impressive. In production it has four critical issues:</p>

  <pre>// auth-manager.ts line 324-327 — CRITICAL: weak password hashing
private hashPassword(password: string): string {
  // In production, use bcrypt or argon2
  return crypto.createHash("sha256").update(password + this.jwtSecret).digest("hex");
}</pre>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Issue</th><th>Severity</th><th>Detail</th></tr>
    <tr><td>SHA-256 password hashing</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-critical">CRITICAL</span></td><td>No work factor, no per-password salt. Rainbow table vulnerable. Must use bcrypt (cost 12+) or argon2id.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>jwtSecret as password salt</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-critical">CRITICAL</span></td><td>If the JWT secret is compromised (e.g. in logs), all password hashes are crackable.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>MFA accepts any 6-digit code</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-high">HIGH</span></td><td>verifyMFA() just checks regex <span class="mono">/^\d{6}$/</span> — no TOTP computation.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Unbounded in-memory stores</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-medium">MEDIUM</span></td><td>tokenBlacklist Set and sessionStore Map grow indefinitely — memory leak under load.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>OAuth2 callback is null stub</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-medium">MEDIUM</span></td><td>Returns null always; documented as production feature.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>JWT expiry not handled on decode path</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-low">LOW</span></td><td>parseJWT() (private) decodes without verification — used internally only, but risky pattern.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>4.3 guard-resolver.ts (276 LOC) — Guard Conflict Resolution</h3>
  <div class="callout callout-good">
    <strong>Best Module in the Codebase</strong>
    The GuardConflictResolver is the most complete, well-reasoned module. The precedence array (<span class="mono">deny &gt; escalate &gt; rewrite &gt; spawn-critic &gt; allow</span>), the conflict type taxonomy (allow_vs_deny, escalate_vs_spawn_critic, rewrite_vs_spawn_critic), and the truth-density tie-breaker are all principled and internally consistent. The proveSafety() and proveTermination() methods — while informal — are a rare and commendable practice of encoding runtime invariants as executable proofs. O(n) complexity is correctly analyzed.
  </div>

  <p>One gap: the GuardConflictResolver is a standalone class and is <strong>never imported or called by nex-runtime.ts</strong>. The core interpreter's <span class="mono">executeGuard()</span> method does not use it. Guard conflict resolution exists only as an independent module, not integrated into execution.</p>

  <h3>4.4 dream-node-engine.ts (299 LOC) — Lateral Reasoning</h3>
  <p>The DreamNodeEngine is conceptually the most innovative module: it provides a self-healing escape mechanism from deadlock states. Triggers include deadlock (pro/contra weight equality), guard contradiction, spawn failure, and merge divergence. Five strategies are enumerated: assumption_inversion, meta_level_shift, orthogonal_dimension, temporal_reframing, agent_spawning_as_dream. However, each strategy implementation returns a hand-crafted static string rather than performing actual LLM invocation or dynamic reasoning. The dream outputs are plausible-sounding but deterministic — they do not actually break deadlocks in an adaptive way.</p>

  <h3>4.5 agent-rewriter.ts (515 LOC) — Self-Modification</h3>
  <p>The AgentRewriter implements a governance model for self-modifying code: proposals are submitted, agents vote, approved proposals are "deployed." The lifecycle is well-designed. However, the deployment step — which should write TypeScript source to disk and restart the interpreter — performs no filesystem operations whatsoever. The <span class="mono">agent-rewriter.ts</span> file has zero <span class="mono">writeFile</span>, <span class="mono">Bun.write</span>, or filesystem calls of any kind. Self-modification is purely in-memory metadata management.</p>

  <h3>4.6 distributed-executor.ts (463 LOC) — Distributed Execution</h3>
  <p>Implements cluster registration, graph partitioning, execution planning, and replication strategy data structures. However, inter-machine communication stubs out at HTTP calls that reference <span class="mono">http://machineId:port/execute</span> — there is no actual network dispatch to real cluster nodes. The local machine runs all partitions using the standard NexInterpreter. This is a well-structured simulation.</p>

  <h3>4.7 storage-adapter.ts (395 LOC) — Persistence</h3>
  <p>Declares support for PostgreSQL, SQLite, MongoDB, and in-memory backends. The in-memory backend is fully functional. The database backends reference methods like <span class="mono">initSqlite()</span>, <span class="mono">initPostgres()</span>, and <span class="mono">initMongoDB()</span> but since <span class="mono">package.json</span> has zero runtime dependencies, no database driver (pg, better-sqlite3, mongodb) is installed. These methods are stubs that print initialization messages.</p>

  <h3>4.8 stdlib-tier2.ts / stdlib-tier3.ts (707 LOC combined)</h3>
  <p>The standard library is implemented as a large object of NexGraph descriptor objects — not as executable functions. <span class="mono">getStdlibFunction()</span> returns a graph object, not a callable. <span class="mono">generateStdlibGraph()</span> creates a NexGraph suitable for NexInterpreter execution. This is architecturally correct for an agent-native runtime where "functions" are graphs — but the graph implementations themselves are templates, not proven implementations. String, math, IO, concurrency, crypto, and AI functions are all represented.</p>
</section>

