<section id="s6" class="chapter">
  <h2 class="section-title">6. Security Findings Catalog (Preliminary)</h2>

  <div class="callout callout-critical">
    <strong>CRITICAL: nex-gateway.ts — Unauthenticated Execute Endpoint</strong>
    The v1.0 gateway (<span class="mono">nex-gateway.ts</span>) exposes <span class="mono">POST /execute</span> with zero authentication. Any caller can submit an arbitrary NexGraph and execute it. Since graph nodes can include "tool" kinds intended to invoke external APIs, this is a potential remote-code-execution surface depending on how tool nodes evolve. The documentation references this gateway as the "first" version but both gateway files exist in the repo simultaneously.
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-critical">
    <strong>CRITICAL: Hardcoded Demo Credentials Logged to stdout</strong>
    <span class="mono">nex-gateway-v1.1.ts</span> lines 246-247 print the following to the console on startup:
    <pre>Email: demo@nex.local | Password: demo-password (user)
Email: admin@nex.local | Password: admin-password (admin)</pre>
    These are also registered as real users in lines 60-61. Any log aggregation system (CloudWatch, Datadog, Splunk) will capture these credentials in plaintext. The admin account has full <span class="mono">users:manage</span> and <span class="mono">audit:read</span> permissions.
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-critical">
    <strong>CRITICAL: Weak Password Hashing</strong>
    <span class="mono">auth-manager.ts:324-327</span>: Passwords are hashed with <span class="mono">SHA-256(password + jwtSecret)</span>. SHA-256 is a fast hash — a modern GPU can compute billions per second. There is no per-password salt. All users share the same "salt" (the JWT secret). A breach of the jwtSecret (which defaults to a random value but can be provided via constructor arg) exposes all passwords simultaneously.
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-high">
    <strong>HIGH: Wildcard CORS</strong>
    Both gateways set <span class="mono">Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *</span>. For an unauthenticated gateway (v1.0) this is less severe. For the authenticated gateway (v1.1) it allows any web origin to make credentialed requests — enabling CSRF attacks from malicious websites if session cookies were used. Should be restricted to known origins.
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-high">
    <strong>HIGH: No Request Body Size Limit</strong>
    Both gateways accumulate the full request body via <span class="mono">req.on("data", chunk => body += chunk)</span> with no size limit. A 1 GB JSON payload will be loaded entirely into memory. This is a trivial memory exhaustion DoS vector. Should enforce a limit of ~10 MB or configurable via environment variable.
  </div>

