    <tr><td>Duplicate data parsing pattern</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-low">LOW</span></td><td>6 methods</td><td>Extract to a <span class="mono">resolveData(node: NexNode)</span> helper</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No-op import in core module</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-low">LOW</span></td><td>1</td><td><span class="mono">import type { } from "node"</span> at nex-runtime.ts line 9</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Unbounded Promise.all</td><td><span class="metric-tag tag-high">HIGH</span></td><td>3 locations</td><td>executeParallel() spawns unlimited parallel promises — no concurrency cap</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>7.3 Data Parsing Anti-Pattern (Repeated 6x)</h3>
  <pre>// Current pattern (repeated in executeGuard, executeRewrite, executeMerge, executeAgent, executeReflect, executeParallel)
const data = typeof node.data === "string" ? JSON.parse(node.data) : node.data as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;;

// Recommended: extract to private helper in NexInterpreter
private resolveData(node: NexNode): Record&lt;string, unknown&gt; {
  if (typeof node.data === "string") {
    try { return JSON.parse(node.data); }
    catch { throw new Error(`Node "${node.id}": invalid JSON in data field`); }
  }
  return node.data as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;;
}</pre>
  <p>The current pattern also silently swallows JSON parse errors — a malformed string data field will throw an unhandled exception that surfaces as a generic runtime crash rather than a meaningful graph validation error.</p>
</section>

